{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599335"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15542"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.94,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8233"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65933"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8233"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6690"},{"type":"tags","id":"6970"},{"type":"tags","id":"8655"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65933"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas receives its arterial blood supply from both the coeliac trunk and the superior mesenteric artery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following embryological junctions does this arterial supply pattern reflect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foregut only","Foregut and hindgut","Foregut and midgut","Midgut only","Midgut and hindgut"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas develops at the junction of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eforegut and midgut\u003C/strong\u003E. The head of the pancreas receives blood supply from branches of the superior mesenteric artery (corresponding to midgut derivatives), while the body and tail receive blood from branches of the coeliac trunk (corresponding to foregut derivatives).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emidgut and hindgut\u003C/strong\u003E junction occurs more distally at the splenic flexure of the colon. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eforegut and hindgut\u003C/strong\u003E do not form a junction as they are separated by the midgut. The pancreas does not develop from the \u003Cstrong\u003Emidgut only\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eforegut only\u003C/strong\u003E, but rather at their junction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pancreas develops at the junction of the foregut and midgut, receiving arterial supply from both the coeliac trunk and superior mesenteric artery.","The embryological origin of an organ determines its blood supply due to the persistence of developmental vascular patterns."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","A-Kader HH, Ghishan FK. The Pancreas. Textbook of Clinical Pediatrics. 2012:1925\u201336. doi: 10.1007/978-3-642-02202-9_198. PMCID: PMC7124086."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id